cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this experiment harness, please cite it as below."
title: "Hierarchical Adaptive Memory for Language Models: A Tiered, Utility-Driven Memory Layer with Variable-Precision Consolidation"
abstract: >
  **Background**: Language models increasingly require information that outlives a single context window, spanning multi-session 
  dialogue and long documents. The prevailing solution is retrieval augmentation around a frozen model, which pays
  the cost of remembering in prompt tokens, stored bytes, and query-time latency, and which typically treats memory as a
  passive external store rather than a participant in computation.
  **Objectives**: This article specifies Hierarchical Adaptive Memory (HAM), a tiered memory layer that organizes information
  into working, episodic, and semantic tiers; routes and fuses retrieved memory into the reasoning blocks; and applies explicit
  utility-driven promotion, forgetting, and consolidation with variable-precision serialization. The aim is a defensible design
  and an honest development-stage account, not a claim of benchmark superiority.
  **Methods**: The implemented proof of concept is an inference-time plug-in for a frozen instruction-tuned model, with
  persistent memory realized through external-context injection and no weight updates. A proposed full layer positions HAM
  alongside Transformer or Mamba blocks with an optionally trainable router and fusion. Evaluation compares HAM against
  no-persistent-memory, uncompressed retrieval, and controlled ablations under a shared frozen model and evaluator.
  **Results**: A real-model proof of concept with a 135M-parameter frozen model on six synthetic examples shows HAM matching
  uncompressed retrieval on task score and retrieval recall while reducing physical store bytes by approximately 3.0x. These
  are proof-of-concept observations, not publication-scale evidence.
  **Conclusions**: HAM offers a coherent, auditable memory layer whose design-level advantages remain hypotheses; publication
